This was so powerful,  in my life I feel like an imposter most of the time. And yet I've overcome addiction,  prison,  suicide,  and trauma. 
Yet still feel this imposter syndrome.

Summary:

People usually see that how their body language affects other people. But their body language effects them also.

When one comes near to the powerful guy, he, she will feel powerless. 

Indicators: When your posture is open, you feel powerful. When your posture is closed, you are hiding yourself.

The non verbal behavior depends upon gender also. Females usually feel powerless than man as per speaker's saying.

So, what to do: Fake it till you make it. Through your posture, you show others that you seem powerful.

Speaker gives answer to 2 questions

1.  Our nonverbals govern how we feel and think about it. Yes, because when we start to change our nonverbals (our testosterone increases (energy level) and cortisol (stress level) decreases. Great leaders and MBA students have high testosterone and low cortisol

2.  Does our body changes our mind : Yes at least till facial expressions.  We feel positive energy, calmness, confidence that is reflected in our mind. 

In the interview, it is good to have good presence. The presence has an impact on your confidence, passion, enthusiasm,  authenticity & comfortability. 

So what to do: Daily 2 minutes, practice of positive postures. 

Speaker's speech ending words: Fake it till you become it.

‚ÄúFake it ill you become it‚Äù- The most impressive statement ever!! As a girl in middle school with so many outstanding fellows, I cried a river along my way to graduation. But through all those tearful years, I know found what my true identity was: Always keep up with your work, and don‚Äôt limit your identity as just a ‚Äúnormal‚Äù student

However, while body language can certainly play a role in self-perception, I believe it‚Äôs important to also recognize the deeper, underlying factors that contribute to confidence and self-esteem, such as personal experiences and internal beliefs. While adopting power poses might offer a temporary boost, lasting change often requires addressing these deeper aspects of self-worth.

What a beautiful story at the end! " Power posing " is a great way to feel less nervous before making a presentation or speech. In case any of you struggle with nerves when presenting see below some other tips:

1. Rehearse your presentation aloud when preparing to get comfortable listening to the sound of your own voice (instead of just reading your slides or notes). Many people panic when they hear themselves speak and the audience are all looking at them.

2. Stand still and have open gestures in the first few moments of your presentation to demonstrate confidence.

3. Avoid awkward pauses especially at the start of your presentation like " em " or " eh " instead pause completely between sentences and especially before and after some of your key points.

4. Take a really big deep breathe before starting your presentation and do your best to smile and enjoy it (even if inside you are not really enjoying it!).

5. Avoid negative self-talk and tell yourself you can do it.

6. Don't speak too quietly at the start of your presentation, instead increase the volume of your voice and speak with passion and conviction.

7. Practice saying the first few lines of your speech or presentation again and again and again. In this way you are likely to make a strong start.

8. Think of an interesting and engaging way to start your presentation such as by telling a story or showing a video or interesting image.

9. Remember 99.9% of the audience want you to do well, so don't overthink it.

10. If you are a nervous presenter, don't panic it's completely normal to feel nerves. Like most things in life the more you practice the better you will get. Keep going and your next presentation will be even better.

I recently gave myself a new habit/daily task to watch one TED talk each weekday in the morning before starting work. I come to the channel, sort the videos by popularity, and watch the next one down the list. The talks before this are very popular for good reasons (mostly) and the information they share is validly helpful, but this one, this one shattered me. This one grabbed 48-years of struggle, 48-years of feeling invisible and powerless, and showed me a different way. Obviously, it's not a magic pill, and I won't be interviewing for CEO of a Fortune 500 company next week (not that I would want to anyway,) but Ann gave us physical, tangible things to do, things to pay attention to, that have proven to help, even in the slightest of manners. Thanks for this, to TED, to Ann Cuddy, and everyone who had a part in the process.
